It's a *somewhat* separate question.  In the old theory, with gravity the
only significant force involved, if the universe was massive enough for
gravity to eventually halt the expansion, it was also massive enough to be
"closed", with positive curvature (like a higher-dimensional sphere),
while insufficient gravity for a halt also meant "open", with negative
curvature (like a higher-dimensional saddle).  There was a lot of doubt,
then, about the exact expansion rate, the universe's mass, and its age,
although the most plausible numbers said that the *visible* mass was
inadequate to halt the expansion.

Courtesy of the work on the microwave background radiation, these numbers
are now tied tightly together, and we have much better measurements too.
To pretty fair accuracy, the universe is *exactly* at the borderline
between the two cases, with *no* large-scale curvature (which does make it
"open", as a boundary case).  This cannot possibly be coincidence, since
any deviation from flatness would grow rapidly with time -- if it's that
close to flat after 13-odd billion years, it was flat, *flat*, FLAT, *FLAT*
at its beginning.

The "cosmic inflation" theory explains this and some other suspicious
uniformities tolerably well:  very early in its history, thanks to some
odd physics, the universe briefly expanded at an immense rate, so what we
now see is a spectacularly-enlarged version of what was originally a very
small universe, too small to have much curvature or other unevenness.  The
underlying physics is still pretty iffy, but the results fit the numbers,
and the competing theories don't.  Closer examination of the microwave
background may reveal more about the details.

Oh, and the visible mass is only about 4.2% of the total mass of the
universe.  Another 20% or so is "dark matter", some sort of exotic matter
that doesn't interact with light at all (it can't be black holes or
anything so tame :-)) but does clump in response to gravity like normal
matter.  The rest -- most of the universe's mass! -- is "dark energy",
whose properties are almost totally unknown; it's a good bet that it also
supplies the pressure that is accelerating the expansion, but we can't say
for sure until we know more about it.

The simplest "dark energy" model has the dark energy, anticipated as
Einstein's "cosmological constant" fudge factor, supplied by the soup of
"virtual particles" constantly appearing and disappearing in empty space.
(This may sound bizarre, but it has measurable consequences -- e.g, the
speed of light is finite because light interacts with those particles --
and particle-physics measurements confirm its existence.)  Unfortunately,
attempts to compute the cosmological constant from virtual-particle theory
yield admittedly-rough guesses(*) that are preposterously large, over 100
orders of magnitude bigger than the largest value it could possibly have
without other observable consequences.

(* The computed value depends on properties of all types of particles,
*including* as-yet-undiscovered ones.  But current particle theory says
the properties of the different particle families are independent, so it
would be a striking coincidence for undiscovered ones to cancel out known
ones to more than 1 or 2 orders of magnitude, and 100+ is just beyond all
belief... )

The universe is a *much* stranger place than we thought twenty years ago.
