would have to intersect Mercury's.  And I think there are contradictory
requirements:  it would have to be big enough to show a noticeable disk
against the Sun, yet small enough not to have been noticed as a comet.
(There are a *lot* of comets that went unnoticed in earlier days -- SOHO's
comet-discovery rate is just astounding -- but they're all pretty small.)

The advantage of invoking near-Earth asteroids as the objects is that they
can be quite close to the observer, and hence need not be large.
