In article &lt;1171459037.509372.13 ... @h3g2000cwc.googlegroups.com&gt;,

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
Ian Parker &lt;ianpark ... @gmail.com&gt; wrote:
&gt;&gt; At least one &quot;Vulcan&quot; sighting is definitely known to have been a very
&gt;&gt; round sunspot..

&gt;What was Vulcan about? In 1846 Adams and Leverrier discovered Neptune
&gt;by predicting its position by means of the perturbations on the orbit
&gt;of Uranus. Towards the end of his life Leverrier attemted to do the
&gt;same thing for Mercury. Mercury's orbit precesses by 43&quot; per century.
&gt;Leverrier explained this by postulating a planet between Mercury and
&gt;The Sun called Vulcan... [but GR explains the precession].
">

Uh, no, that's by no means the full story.

People were looking for intra-Mercurian planets considerably before
Leverrier's 1860 announcement.  The discovery of Uranus in 1781
established that there were more planets than the classical naked-eye
ones(*), so it was not unreasonable that there might be undiscovered
planets inside Mercury's orbit as well as outside Saturn's.  For example,
Schwabe discovered the sunspot cycle while planet-hunting, starting in
1826.

(* Uranus actually is a naked-eye object, given good eyes and dark skies,
but was not noticed in classical times because it's faint and moves quite
slowly. )

Moreover, Leverrier initially proposed that the unknown mass disturbing
Mercury's orbit might be an intra-Mercurian *asteroid belt* rather than a
single planet, probably because he knew that Herrick had already made a
systematic search for intra-Mercurian planets (in response to the
discovery of Neptune) and had found none.

(Indeed, the object that Lescarbault observed in transit -- which
Leverrier eventually named Vulcan -- was clearly too small to account for
Mercury's orbit by itself, although it was about right to be the largest
object in Leverrier's hypothetical asteroid belt.)

Leverrier's theoretical support for intra-Mercurian object(s) strengthened
interest in the possibility, yes, but it wasn't the sole reason that
people went looking for them.

(Reference:  Willy Ley's "Watchers of the Skies".)

Oh, and incidentally, Mercury's orbit precesses 5599.7 arcseconds per
century -- the 43 arcseconds in question is not the precession rate, but
the (then) *unexplained* part of the precession rate.  Most of the
precession is caused by well-understood factors like perturbations by the
other planets.  The minuteness of the discrepancy against a background of
large known causes, plus the difficulty of getting good observations of
Mercury at all, is why it took someone of Leverrier's talents to establish
that the discrepancy was real and beyond easy explanation.

(Reference:  Skinner's "Relativity for Scientists and Engineers".)
