Yes, it's well worth doing, and efforts in that direction are already
underway, e.g. LIGO.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;As the only way forward is to take a look, the conclusion that NOBODY
&gt;should go to Mars is inescapable.
">

Um, what are you talking about?  There are currently *no* plans to send
anyone to Mars.  Bush's "Vision for Space Exploration" marching orders to
NASA include Mars only as a far-distant long-term goal, not as something
that significant money will be spent on any time soon.  (VSE's near-term
focus is on shuttle replacement, and its medium-term goal is the Moon.)

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;LISA is scheduled for 2012. Will it fly? Of course not.
">

If it doesn't, that's likely to have more to do with the difficulty of
doing LISA than with competition for funds from manned spaceflight.  LISA
is a large, complex, technologically-challenging mission, which is almost
certain to hit cost overruns and delays just because it's *hard*.

Indeed, looking at current status, there's just no way that LISA will fly
in 2012, the *original* target date -- it would appear that you're a bit
behind the news.  ESA's LISA Pathfinder mission, an essential preliminary
which will test some of the key LISA technologies in space, is itself
nearly two years behind schedule -- some technology that they thought was
off-the-shelf wasn't -- and probably won't launch until 2010.  That puts
LISA launch in 2014-2015 at the earliest, I'd say, and indeed, 2017 seems
to be the current target for when LISA will actually be in position,
checked out, and observing.
